Questions:¶


1- is there any co-relation between the attendance and the Age or gender of the person?
2- is there any co-relation between the attendance and the medical condition of the person, that includes (Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handicap)?
3- is reminding the patient with an SMS helps?
4- what effect does the scholarship have?
5- how different is the medical profile of people who attend and who don't?
6- what effect does the duration between Scheduling and the actucal date have?
7- does the day on which the appointment is scheduled make a difference?
8- what effect does the Neighbourhood have?

Data Cleaning:¶

1- AppointmentDay and ScheduledDay are to be datetime format.
2- the time component of the AppointmentDay is missing so we need to ignore that component in the ScheduledDay in order to make the data consistent and to extract a consistent waiting time, then we are dropping the two columns.
3- subtract the two dates to get the waiting time for each patient.
4- there are columns need to be ranamed: No-show to Attendance, Handcap to Handicap, Hipertension to Hypertension.
5- the new attendance column will be better understood if we replaced the Yes and NO values with ones and zeros.. note that the No meant that the patient did really attend.
6- Age categories are important as ages are too many and creating categories would ease the analysis to some extend.
7- patient ID and appointment ID are irrelevant to the analysis so we will drop them.

inter=['Scholarship','Hypertension','Diabetes','Alcoholism','SMS_received','Handicaped'] #list of all interest columns.

for col in inter: #loop to plot graphs of counts and percentages.
    data=df.groupby(col)['Attendance'].value_counts()
    data_per=df.groupby(col)['Attendance'].value_counts(normalize=True)*100
    x_labels=['No '+col+' Attended','No '+col+' Missed',col+" Attended",col+" missed"]
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    plt.bar(x_labels ,data,color=['b','r','b','r'],alpha=.7,width=.2)
    plt.title('count of appointments Vs '+col)
    plt.xlabel('status')
    plt.ylabel('Number of appointments')
    for index, value in zip(x_labels,data.values):
        plt.text(index,value,str(value))
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    plt.bar(x_labels,data_per,color=['b','r','b','r'],alpha=.7,width=.2)
    plt.title('percent of attendance Vs '+col)
    plt.xlabel('status')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage')

    for index, value in zip(x_labels,data_per):
        plt.text(index,value,str(value)+"%")

Conclusions¶


Number of patients attended their appointments is higher than who missed by around 4 folds.

Females has the larger number of appointments, Males tend to attend appoinments more, but with slight margin over females.

Most age group present are newborn patients and more appointments are missed as we move for older age but due to the low number of appointments we can't be sure so we have to look to means and percetages.

Mean attendance for the pregnant woman and the group from 100-110 is one due to the lack of data (only one pregnant woman).

The distribution of means in the middle shows that from ages 10 to 70 people tend not to miss this appointments more as they grow up, then the means falls as they get pass 70.

People with a scholarship constitute a small portion tend to have lower attendance mean.

people suffering from hypertension or diabetes or Handicaped are also a small portion of the data but they have slightly higher attendance mean.

Alcoholic people are the least faction in terms of numbers and they have attendance mean higher than who are not but the difference is highly negligible.

Receiving an SMS reminder has lower the attendance mean.

the health profile of people who attend is somehow identical to those who miss.

Mean time of waiting is lower for people who attended their appointments.

No appointments on Sundays, mean attendane across the week seems equal, with slightly lower attendance mean on Saturdays.

For top 10 neighbourhoods in terms of appointments count, attendance percentages does not seem to be affected by the place.

Limitations:¶


1- appointments are scheduled over short span of time, this limited understanding the effect of seasons, holidays on the showing up of patients.
2- Some data about the distance between the patient and the neighbourhood would be useful.
3- indications of the seriousness of illness would be helpful too.
4-Dataset is missing key informations like the prices, employment status of patients.
5- for some cases there is small number of people reported such as (one pregnant woman, small number of alchoholics), this somehow limited the analysis.
